(* ### Problem
 In acute triangle $ABC$, $\angle A = 68^\circ$.  Let $O$ be the circumcenter of triangle $ABC$.  Find $\angle OBC$, in degrees.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, O;

A = (1,2);
B = (0,0);
C = (3,0);
O = circumcenter(A,B,C);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(circumcircle(A,B,C));
draw(B--O);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
dot("$O$", O, NE);
[/asy] The final Answer is 22^\circ
 ### Proof
 Since $O$ is the center of the circle passing through $A$, $B$, and $C$, $\angle BOC = 2 \angle BAC = 2 \cdot 68^\circ = 136^\circ$. [asy] unitsize(1.5 cm); pair A, B, C, O; A = (1,2); B = (0,0); C = (3,0);
 O = circumcenter(A,B,C); draw(A--B--C--cycle); draw(circumcircle(A,B,C)); draw(B--O--C); label("$A$", A, N); label("$B$", B, SW); label("$C$", C, SE); dot("$O$", O, N); [/asy] Since $BO = CO$ (both are equal to the circumradius of triangle $ABC$), triangle $BOC$ is isosceles.
 Hence, $\angle OBC = (180^\circ - \angle BOC)/2 = (180^\circ - 136^\circ)/2 = \boxed{22^\circ}$.
 *)

theorem
fixes A B C O :: "real * real"
and angle :: "(real * real) ⇒ (real * real) ⇒ (real * real) ⇒ real"
assumes h0 : "angle A B C = 68"
and h1 : "O = circumcenter A B C"
shows  "angle O B C = 22"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer

